Network communication

Data Packets: The Basics of Network Communication
•	Data packets are the fundamental units of information transferred across a network, containing details about their destination, origin, and content.
•	Similar to a physical letter, a data packet includes a header with IP and MAC addresses, a protocol number, the message body, and a footer to signal its completion.
Network Performance and Security
•	Network performance can be assessed by bandwidth, which measures the amount of data received per second, calculated by dividing data quantity by time.
•	Security personnel monitor bandwidth and speed for irregularities, as these can be indicators of a network attack, and packet sniffing is used to inspect data packets for security purposes.


TCP (Transmission Control Protocol)
•	TCP is an internet communication protocol that enables two devices to establish a connection and stream data.
•	It organizes data for network transmission, establishes connections, and ensures data packets reach their intended destinations.
IP (Internet Protocol)
•	IP provides standards for routing and addressing data packets as they move between devices on a network.
•	An IP address acts as a unique identifier for each private network.
Port Numbers
•	Ports are software-based locations within a network device's operating system that organize data sending and receiving.
•	Port numbers allow computers to segment network traffic, prioritize operations, and instruct receiving devices on how to handle information.

Layers of the TCP/IP Model
•	Network Access Layer: This first layer handles the creation of data packets and their transmission, involving hardware devices like cables and switches.
•	Internet Layer: The second layer attaches IP addresses to data packets, indicating sender and receiver locations, and determines how networks connect.
Data Flow and Interaction
•	Transport Layer: This layer includes protocols that control network traffic flow, manage error control, and ensure smooth data transmission.
•	Application Layer: The final layer defines how data packets interact with receiving devices, organizing functions such as file transfers and email services.

TCP/IP Model Overview
•	The TCP/IP model is a framework for visualizing how data is organized and transmitted across a network, crucial for network engineers and security analysts to identify disruptions or threats.
•	It consists of four layers: network access, internet, transport, and application, which help security professionals analyze the impact of attacks based on involved processes.
Layers of the TCP/IP Model
•	Network Access Layer: This layer handles the creation and transmission of data packets across a network, involving physical hardware like hubs and cables, and protocols such as ARP for mapping IP to MAC addresses.
•	Internet Layer: Responsible for delivering data to the destination host, potentially on a different network, by attaching IP addresses to data packets and determining the appropriate delivery protocol (e.g., IP and ICMP).
•	Transport Layer: Manages data delivery between systems or networks, controlling traffic flow with protocols like TCP for reliable, connection-oriented data streaming and UDP for connectionless, performance-sensitive applications.
•	Application Layer: Similar to the application, presentation, and session layers of the OSI model, this layer defines accessible internet services and applications, using protocols like HTTP, SMTP, and DNS to govern data packet interaction with receiving devices.
TCP/IP Model versus OSI Model
•	Both the TCP/IP and OSI models are conceptual frameworks that standardize networking and divide communication into layers, helping professionals visualize network processes and troubleshoot issues.
•	The TCP/IP model is a simplified version of the OSI model, with the TCP/IP model having four layers compared to the OSI model's seven.

TCP/IP Model vs. OSI Model
•	The TCP/IP model is a four-layer framework that helps professionals visualize data organization and transmission, aiding in identifying disruptions or security threats.
•	The OSI model is a standardized, seven-layer concept describing how computers communicate and send data, used by network and security professionals to discuss problems or threats.
The Seven Layers of the OSI Model
•	Application Layer (Layer 7): This layer directly involves the end-user and includes protocols that allow software applications to connect to the internet, such as HTTP/HTTPS for web browsing, SMTP for email, and DNS for translating domain names to IP addresses.
•	Presentation Layer (Layer 6): Functions at this layer include data translation, encryption, and compression, ensuring data is in a format understandable by applications on both sending and receiving systems.
•	Session Layer (Layer 5): This layer establishes, maintains, and terminates connections (sessions) between two devices, handling authentication, reconnection, and setting checkpoints during data transfer.
•	Transport Layer (Layer 4): Responsible for delivering data between devices, this layer manages data transfer speed, flow, and segmentation of data into smaller pieces for easier transmission, using protocols like TCP and UDP.
•	Network Layer (Layer 3): This layer oversees the routing of data packets between different networks, using IP addresses to deliver them to their intended destinations.
•	Data Link Layer (Layer 2): This layer organizes the sending and receiving of data packets within a single network, involving devices like switches and network interface cards, and protocols such as NCP, HDLC, and SDLC.
•	Physical Layer (Layer 1): This is the hardware layer, encompassing physical components like hubs, modems, cables, and wiring, responsible for translating data packets into a stream of 0s and 1s for physical transmission.

Local and wide network communication

IP Addresses: Identification and Types
•	An IP address is a unique string of characters that identifies a device's location on the internet, similar to a mailing address for a house.
•	There are two main types: IPv4, which uses four sets of 1-3 digit numbers separated by decimals, and IPv6, which uses 32 characters to accommodate the increasing number of internet-connected devices.
Public vs. Private IP Addresses
•	Public IP addresses are assigned by your internet service provider and are connected to your geographic location, with all devices on a network sharing the same public-facing IP.
•	Private IP addresses are used for communication between devices on the same local network and are not visible to the wider internet.
MAC Addresses: Device-Specific Identifiers
•	A MAC address is a unique alphanumeric identifier assigned to each physical device on a network.
•	Switches use MAC addresses and a MAC address table to direct data packets to the correct device on a network.

Network Layer Operations
•	The network layer handles the addressing and delivery of data packets, directing them from a source to a destination device across the internet.
•	Routers use the destination IP address within a packet's header to route it, storing this information in routing tables for future use.
IPv4 Packet Format
•	An IPv4 packet consists of a header (20 to 60 bytes) and a data section, with the header containing crucial routing information like source and destination IP addresses.
•	Key fields in the IPv4 header include "Time to Live" (TTL) to prevent indefinite forwarding, "Protocol" to specify the data's protocol, and "Header Checksum" for corruption detection.
IPv4 vs. IPv6
•	IPv4 addresses are 4 bytes long, allowing for approximately 4.3 billion unique addresses, while IPv6 addresses are 16 bytes long, supporting a significantly larger number of addresses (340 undecillion).
•	IPv6 was developed to address IPv4 address exhaustion and offers a simpler header format, more efficient routing, and improved security features compared to IPv4.

Connect and Protect: Module 2

Network protocols
The Role of Network Protocols
•	Network protocols are sets of rules that govern how devices on a network communicate, ensuring data is delivered in the correct order and structure.
•	They are essential for the proper functioning of networks, from accessing websites to transferring data.
Key Network Protocols in Action
•	TCP (Transmission Control Protocol): Establishes a connection and verifies devices before data streaming, often through a "handshake" process.
•	ARP (Address Resolution Protocol): Determines the MAC address of the next router or device to ensure data packets are sent to the correct location.
•	HTTPS (Hypertext Transfer Protocol Secure): Provides a secure method for communication between client and web servers, encrypting data using SSL/TLS.
•	DNS (Domain Name System): Translates human-readable internet domain names into numerical IP addresses, allowing devices to locate websites.
Protocols and Security
•	Secure protocols like HTTPS are crucial for protecting sensitive information from malicious actors by encrypting data during transmission.
•	Understanding network protocols is a fundamental skill for security analysts, as they are integral to daily activities and securing networks.

Common network protocols
Overview of Network Protocols
•	A network protocol is a set of rules that govern how devices communicate and exchange data over a network.
•	Protocols are crucial for network communication, but security analysts must understand their vulnerabilities, as malicious actors can exploit them.
Categories of Network Protocols
•	Network protocols are broadly categorized into communication protocols, management protocols, and security protocols.
•	While there are many protocols, entry-level security analysts should focus on understanding the key ones discussed in this reading.
Specific Protocol Examples
•	Communication Protocols: Examples include TCP (reliable, connection-oriented), UDP (fast, connectionless), HTTP (insecure web communication), and DNS (translates domain names to IP addresses).
•	Management Protocols: SNMP (monitors and manages network devices) and ICMP (reports data transmission errors) are key examples.
•	Security Protocols: HTTPS (secure web communication using SSL/TLS encryption) and SFTP (secure file transfer using SSH) are vital for data security.

Additional network protocols
Network Address Translation (NAT)
•	Function: NAT allows multiple devices on a private network to share a single public IP address when accessing the internet.
•	Mechanism: Routers replace private IP addresses with a public IP for outgoing traffic and reverse this process for incoming responses.
Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP)
•	Purpose: DHCP is a management protocol that automatically assigns unique IP addresses to devices on a network.
•	Operation: It works with the router to provide devices with necessary network configuration details, including IP addresses, DNS server addresses, and default gateways.
Address Resolution Protocol (ARP)
•	Role: ARP translates IP addresses into MAC addresses, which are unique hardware identifiers for network interface cards.
•	Process: Devices use ARP to discover the MAC address corresponding to a known IP address within the same local network.
Remote Access Protocols
•	Telnet: An application layer protocol for remote system connections, but it sends information in clear text, making it insecure.
•	Secure Shell (SSH): A more secure alternative to Telnet, SSH provides encrypted communication and secure authentication for remote access.
Email Protocols
•	Post Office Protocol (POP): Used to retrieve emails from a mail server, typically downloading them to a local device and optionally deleting them from the server.
•	Internet Message Access Protocol (IMAP): Allows users to access and manage emails directly on the mail server, enabling synchronization across multiple devices.
•	Simple Mail Transfer Protocol (SMTP): Responsible for sending and routing emails from the sender to the recipient's mail server.
Port Numbers and Security
•	Significance: Port numbers help network devices direct data packets to the correct applications or services.
•	Firewall Application: Firewalls can be configured to filter network traffic based on port numbers, enhancing security by blocking unwanted access.

Protocols and their associated port numbers
•	DHCP:
o	UDP port 67 (servers)
o	UDP port 68 (clients)
•	ARP: None (it's a Layer 2 protocol)
•	Telnet: TCP port 23
•	SSH: TCP port 22
•	POP3:
o	TCP/UDP port 110 (unencrypted)
o	TCP/UDP port 995 (encrypted, SSL/TLS)
•	IMAP:
o	TCP port 143 (unencrypted)
o	TCP port 993 (encrypted, SSL/TLS)
•	SMTP:
o	TCP/UDP Port 25 (unencrypted)
o	TCP/UDP port 587 (encrypted, TLS)
•	HTTP: Port 80
•	DNS: UDP port 53 (can switch to TCP for large replies)
•	HTTPS: Uses encryption from SSL/TLS (typically port 443, though not explicitly stated in this reading for HTTPS itself, it's implied by the use of SSL/TLS)

Wireless protocols
IEEE 802.11: The Foundation of Wi-Fi
•	IEEE 802.11 is a set of standards that define communications for wireless Local Area Networks (LANs).
•	The Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE) is the organization responsible for maintaining these Wi-Fi standards.
Evolution of Wi-Fi Security
•	Wi-Fi protocols have continuously evolved to enhance security and reliability, aiming to match the security levels of wired connections.
•	Wi-Fi Protected Access (WPA) was introduced in 2004 as a wireless security protocol, with subsequent versions like WPA2 and WPA3 offering advanced encryption and improved security.
Importance for Security Analysts
•	As a security analyst, understanding these protocols is crucial for ensuring the security of wireless connections within an organization.
•	The continuous development of Wi-Fi security measures highlights the ongoing need for vigilance and adaptation in network security.

The evolution of wireless security protocols
Early Wireless Communication and Wi-Fi
•	The internet initially relied on physical cables, with wireless expansion occurring after the mid-1980s with designated radio wave frequencies.
•	Wi-Fi, a marketing term by the Wi-Fi Alliance, refers to a set of standards (IEEE 802.11) for wireless LAN communication.
Evolution of Wireless Security Protocols
•	WEP (Wired Equivalent Privacy): Developed in 1999, WEP aimed to provide wired-level privacy but is now considered high-risk due to vulnerabilities.
•	WPA (Wi-Fi Protected Access): Introduced in 2003 as a transitional measure, WPA improved upon WEP by using TKIP and larger encryption keys, but still had vulnerabilities like KRACK attacks.
Advanced Wireless Security: WPA2 and WPA3
•	WPA2: Released in 2004, WPA2 uses AES and CCMP for stronger encryption and is the current security standard, though it remains vulnerable to KRACK attacks.
•	WPA3: The latest protocol, WPA3, addresses KRACK attack vulnerabilities with Simultaneous Authentication of Equals (SAE) and offers increased encryption (128-bit, with optional 192-bit for Enterprise mode).

