Secure networks against Denial of Service (DoS) attacks
Denial of Service (DoS) attacks
Denial of Service (DoS) Attacks
•	DoS attacks flood a network or server with traffic to disrupt normal business operations, potentially leading to financial losses and increased vulnerability to other security threats.
•	A Distributed Denial of Service (DDoS) attack uses multiple devices from various locations to flood the target network, making it more effective due to the sheer volume of traffic.
Network-Level DoS Attacks
•	SYN Flood Attack: This attack exploits the TCP handshake process by sending numerous SYN requests to a server. If the number of requests exceeds available ports, the server becomes overwhelmed and crashes.
•	ICMP Flood Attack: Attackers repeatedly send ICMP packets to a server, forcing it to send ICMP replies. This consumes bandwidth for both incoming and outgoing traffic, leading to a server crash.
Ping of Death Attack
•	This DoS attack involves sending an oversized ICMP packet (larger than 64 kilobytes) to a vulnerable system. The excessively large packet overloads the system, causing it to crash.

