This reading introduces network protocol analyzers, focusing on tcpdump as a key tool for cybersecurity analysts to monitor and analyze network traffic.
Understanding Network Protocol Analyzers
•	Network protocol analyzers, also known as packet sniffers, capture and analyze data traffic within a network to identify suspicious activity.
•	Common analyzers include SolarWinds NetFlow Traffic Analyzer, ManageEngine OpManager, Azure Network Watcher, Wireshark, and tcpdump.
tcpdump: A Command-Line Analyzer
•	tcpdump is a popular, lightweight, command-line network protocol analyzer that uses the open-source libpcap library.
•	It provides brief packet analysis, converting key network traffic information into human-readable formats, and is compatible with Unix-based operating systems like Linux and macOS.
Interpreting and Using tcpdump Output
•	tcpdump output includes important information such as timestamp, source IP and port, and destination IP and port, which helps in understanding network communication.
•	Network protocol analyzers are used to establish baselines for network traffic, detect malicious activity, troubleshoot performance issues, and identify unauthorized communication, though they can also be misused by attackers to capture sensitive data.


Network attack tactics and defense
Malicious packet sniffing
Understanding Packet Sniffing
•	Packet sniffing involves using software tools to capture and analyze data packets as they travel across a network.
•	These packets contain valuable information in their body, such as personal messages, financial details, and credit card numbers, along with sender and receiver IP addresses in the header.
Malicious Use of Packet Sniffing
•	Threat actors can use packet sniffing to gain unauthorized access to information by inserting themselves into an authorized connection between devices.
•	They can also manipulate data in transit, such as altering bank account numbers, to their advantage.
Types of Packet Sniffing and Prevention
•	Passive packet sniffing involves reading data packets in transit without altering them, similar to someone reading mail they are delivering.
•	Active packet sniffing involves manipulating data packets in transit, such as redirecting them or changing their content.
•	To prevent malicious packet sniffing, it's recommended to use a VPN for data encryption, ensure websites use HTTPS, and avoid unprotected public Wi-Fi networks.

IP Spoofing
Understanding IP Spoofing
•	IP spoofing involves an attacker impersonating an authorized system to gain network access, bypassing firewall rules.
•	The attacker modifies the sender's IP address in data packets to match an authorized user or system.
Types of IP Spoofing Attacks
•	On-path attacks: The attacker positions themselves between two communicating devices, intercepts data, and then uses the sniffed IP and MAC addresses to impersonate either device.
•	Replay attacks: A malicious actor intercepts data packets and either delays them to cause connection issues or repeats them later to impersonate an authorized user.
•	Smurf attacks: This combines a Distributed Denial of Service (DDoS) attack with IP spoofing, where an attacker floods a target's spoofed IP address with packets, overwhelming the system.
Protecting Against IP Spoofing
•	Encryption: Always implement encryption to prevent malicious actors from reading data in transit.
•	Firewall Configuration: Configure firewalls to reject incoming traffic from the internet that has an IP address matching the local network, as such traffic should originate from within the private network.

Overview of interception tactics
Packet Sniffing
•	Packet sniffing involves capturing and inspecting data packets across a network.
•	Malicious actors can set a device's Network Interface Card (NIC) to "promiscuous mode" to capture all network traffic, even packets not addressed to that specific device.
IP Spoofing
•	After sniffing packets, attackers can impersonate authorized devices' IP and MAC addresses to perform IP spoofing attacks.
•	Firewalls can help prevent IP spoofing by refusing unauthorized IP packets and suspicious traffic.
Common IP Spoofing Attacks
•	On-path attacks (also known as meddler-in-the-middle attacks) occur when a hacker intercepts communication between two trusted devices, potentially collecting sensitive information or redirecting DNS lookups to malicious sites.
•	Smurf attacks combine IP spoofing with a denial-of-service (DoS) technique, flooding a network with unwanted traffic by spoofing an authorized user's IP address and sending packets to the broadcast address, overwhelming network servers.

